<paper id="1501933381"><title>Learning Query Rules for Optimizing Databases with Update Rules</title><year>1996</year><authors><author org="Universite d'Orléans" id="2917365365">Dominique Laurent</author><author org="Universite d'Orléans" id="642242693">Christel Vrain</author></authors><n_citation>5</n_citation><doc_type>Conference</doc_type><references><reference>115237046</reference><reference>138414955</reference><reference>1480806338</reference><reference>1496528554</reference><reference>1511711492</reference><reference>1558832481</reference><reference>1565236324</reference><reference>1756530980</reference><reference>1968513265</reference><reference>1999138184</reference><reference>2003531456</reference><reference>2111901740</reference><reference>2155322595</reference></references><venue id="1180646617" type="C">Logic in Databases</venue><doi>10.1007/BFb0031740</doi><keywords><keyword weight="0.61996">Inductive logic programming</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Logic program</keyword><keyword weight="0.45566">Data mining</keyword><keyword weight="0.6125">Query language</keyword><keyword weight="0.69714">Deductive database</keyword><keyword weight="0.46438">Computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.46925">Theoretical computer science</keyword><keyword weight="0.43902">Predicate (grammar)</keyword><keyword weight="0.0">Extensional definition</keyword><keyword weight="0.54387">Dependency graph</keyword><keyword weight="0.44758">Database</keyword></keywords><publisher>Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg</publisher><abstract>In this paper, we are interested in coupling deductive database approaches and inductive logic programming. We focus on a particular approach to updating Datalogneg databases based on two kinds of rules, namely update rules and query rules. In this approach, every fact to be inserted or to be deleted is stored in the database, in order to handle updates over extensional or intensional predicates in a sound and deterministic way.</abstract></paper>